# Auto-documentation

When you add or change behavior in this project, update docs in the **same task** — do not wait for the user to ask.

**Batching (context hygiene):** do **one** README/GOALS edit pass at the end of the feature, not after every micro-change. Collect doc notes mentally (or in the plan) and apply them together.

## What to update

| Change | Update |
|--------|--------|
| New/changed CLI flags, defaults, profiles | [`README.md`](README.md) — relevant section + flag table |
| New script or workflow (`import_70mai.py`, `compose_70mai.py`, etc.) | [`README.md`](README.md) — usage, examples, output paths |
| Project goals or scope | [`GOALS.md`](GOALS.md) |
| Non-obvious sync/encoding/audio logic | Short explanation in README (thresholds, fallbacks) |

## README conventions (this repo)

- **Import**: SD layout, `--scan`, date/time filters, output under `video/Output/`
- **Compose**: vertical 3-cam layout, sync by screen recording time, `--profile` / HW flags, **audio auto-analysis** (`--audio`, `--audio-offset`, thresholds)
- Include copy-paste command examples for common tasks (dry-run, 60s test, 10 min export)
- Keep flag tables aligned with `--help` output

## When to skip

- Pure refactors with no user-visible change
- Internal-only edits (comments, formatting)
- User explicitly says "no docs" or question-only / review-only task

## Done criteria

Before finishing a feature task, confirm README (and GOALS if needed) reflects what you shipped. Mention doc updates briefly in the final reply.
